ODE XI. To LYDss.

HERMES, taught by whom Amphion's throat Charmed into motion stones and senseless things, And thou sweet shell, that dost with dulcet note Make music from thy seven melodicus strings,

Thou once nor sweet, nor voluble, but now In fane, or rich man's feast, a welcome guest, Give to my song the charmer's might, to bow Lyde's unyielding ear, and unrelenting breast!

Lyde, who, like a filly full of play,

That frisks and gambols o'er the meadows wide, And fears e'en to be touched, will never stay

To list the burning tale that woos her for a bride.

Thou listening woods canst lead, and tigers fell, And stay the rapid rivers in their course3 Yea, the grim janitor of ghastly hell Crouched on his post, subdued by thy persuasive force;
